  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Enhanced Resiliency and Living Conditions for Vulnerable Communities Addressing Economic, Health, and Food Security Challenges due to Impacts of COVID-19 in Sierra Leone</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Sierra Leone is a low-income country marked by food insecurity and limited access to livelihoods. Food availability and affordability have increasingly become low. As the country relies on imported goods, including most of its staple foods, food prices spiked across the country, leading many households in a spiral of poverty. According to the Household Hunger Scale, 73 percent of households suffer from hunger, among which six percent suffer from severe hunger. As a response to these urgent challenges, the International Organization for Migration (IOM) and the United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime (UNODC) are jointly implementing a programme which seeks to strengthen the capacity of the Government and communities to prevent and mitigate public health challenges, and provide resources to improve livelihoods and address obstacles to improved food security for enhanced community resilience.</narrative>
  </description>
